# Backend Inline Documentation

Teaches the **chat-app.ts documentation style** for `src/` backend code. Use alongside `main-rules/05-code-docs.mdc` (file headers, TSDoc contracts). This skill owns **how the body reads** — step comments and orchestration-class structure.

**Canonical reference:** `src/chat/chat-app.ts`  
**Secondary references:** `src/rag/rag-app.ts` (`parseDocument`, `uploadDocument`), `src/scenario-generation/scenario-service.ts`

## When to apply

- New or substantially changed **orchestration classes** (ChatApp, RAGApp, ScenarioService, memory agent)
- Multi-phase methods: LLM + RAG + persist, grading pipelines, upload/parse, migration backfills
- Any public method where the *procedure* is not obvious from helper names alone

## Class-level block

After the file header, document the main export class with responsibilities and key features:

```typescript
/**
 * ChatApp Class
 *
 * This module provides the ChatApp class for managing chat conversations,
 * RAG integration, and message handling for the EngE-AI platform.
 *
 * Key Features:
 * - Streaming chat responses from LLM
 * - RAG document retrieval from Qdrant
 * - Chat inactivity timer management
 *
 * @author: EngE-AI Team
 * @version: 2.0.0
 * @since: 2026-03-16
 */
export class ChatApp { ... }
```

| Element | Rule |
|---------|------|
| Title line | `{Name} Class` or `{Name}` for non-class modules |
| Prose | 1–2 sentences on layer boundary (orchestration vs routes vs mongo delegate) |
| Key Features | Bullet list of **non-obvious** capabilities — skip trivial getters |
| `@since` | Optional on long-lived classes; use `@date` on file header for new files |

## Method JSDoc

**Public, exported, and non-obvious private methods** — use the four-part contract below.

### Four-part shape (required)

| Section | Rule |
|---------|------|
| **1. Title** | `{functionName} - {main purpose}` on line 1 |
| **2. Explicit properties** | 1–2 prose lines: return shape (`{ feedback }`), side effects (persist, LLM), branch/tier behavior |
| **3. Params** | `@param` for **every** parameter — domain role, not signature restatement |
| **4. Return** | `@returns` — shape, success value, and failure/throw when non-obvious; add `@throws` when applicable |

```typescript
/**
 * feedbackPracticePart - Practice check-answer: friendly TA feedback via structured LLM output (no grade).
 *
 * Tier selects the prompt path: `socratic` returns hint-style feedback only; `descriptive`
 * evaluates the answer and appends the model answer server-side. Always returns `{ feedback }`.
 *
 * @param questionBody - Parent scenario stem shown to the LLM for context
 * @param subQuestion - Target sub-part (prompt, modelAnswer, type)
 * @param studentAnswer - Student submission text for this sub-question
 * @param tier - `socratic` (default) or `descriptive` (evaluation + model answer reveal)
 * @returns `{ feedback }` TA-facing string; throws when structured LLM output is empty
 */
```

**Canonical references:** `feedbackPracticePart`, `submitStudentResponse` in `scenario-service.ts`; `restoreChatFromDatabase` in `chat-app.ts`.

| Do | Don't |
|----|-------|
| Lead with `{name} -` then explicit return shape / side effects | Skip the explicit-properties block when return shape or branching is non-obvious |
| Document every `@param`, including defaulted or optional args | Restate the signature (`@param chatId - The chat id`) |
| `@returns` describes shape and failure modes | `@returns void` on constructors |
| JSDoc private helpers only when behavior is not obvious from the name | JSDoc every private one-liner |

## Inline step comments (two tiers)

### Tier 1 — Simple steps (default)

One full-sentence `//` comment **immediately before** each logical step:

```typescript
// Reset the inactivity timer since user is actively using this chat
this.resetChatTimer(chatId);

// Validate chat exists
if (!this.conversations.has(chatId)) {
    throw new Error('Chat not found');
}

// Remove from conversations map
this.conversations.delete(chatId);
```

Use for: validation, map/array mutations, timer cleanup, branch intent.

### Tier 2 — Numbered pipeline blocks (orchestration methods)

When a method has **4+ distinct phases** (RAG → LLM → persist → side effects), use banner blocks:

```typescript
// ====================================================================
// STEP 1: Add user message to conversation and history
// ====================================================================

// Add user message to both LLM conversation and chatHistory for frontend sync
const addedUserMessage = this.addUserMessage(chatId, message, userId, courseName);

// ====================================================================
// STEP 2: RAG DOCUMENT RETRIEVAL (for CURRENT user message)
// ====================================================================
```

| Use STEP banners | Use simple `//` only |
|------------------|-------------------|
| `sendUserMessage`-scale pipelines | CRUD delegates, sanitizers, index creation |
| Generate → sanitize → persist loops | Single LLM call + return |
| Exam validate → batch grade → atomic append | Getters, thin route handlers |

Keep **sub-steps** under each banner as Tier 1 comments.

## Interface and export docs

Exported request/context interfaces at module top get a one-line or short block:

```typescript
/** Input for batch exam submission — one answer per visible sub-question. */
export interface ScenarioSubmitExamInput { ... }
```

Module-level convenience exports:

```typescript
/** Module-level wrapper around the process-wide {@link ScenarioService} singleton. */
export async function generateScenarioQuestions(...) { ... }
```

## Section dividers in large files

Use a short banner between unrelated groups (mongo delegate pattern):

```typescript
// =====================================================
// Embedded studentResponses + solution gate
// =====================================================
```

## Prompt and constant modules

- `scenario-*-modules.ts`, `rag-prompts.ts`: file header + `/** Prompt module: NAME */` above each export — **no** step comments inside template strings.
- `scenario-*-prompt.ts`: file header; JSDoc on `build*Prompt` / `build*UserTurn` describing XML shape and escaping.

## Checklist (before marking Document phase done)

- [ ] File header per `05-code-docs.mdc`
- [ ] Main class has Key Features (or concise responsibility prose)
- [ ] Every **public** method uses four-part JSDoc (`{name} -`, explicit properties when needed, `@param`, `@returns`)
- [ ] Orchestration methods use STEP banners; other multi-step methods use Tier 1 comments
- [ ] Branch comments explain **why** (e.g. instructor preview vs student persist)
- [ ] No permanent `// DEBUG:` / `// TEMP:` comments

## Anti-patterns

- Comment every line (`// increment i`)
- Duplicate JSDoc and step comment with the same words
- STEP banners on 10-line helpers
- Enumerate every method inside the class JSDoc (use Key Features instead)
